at the ileocaecal junction and an additional isolated segment of inflammation in the transverse colon.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following pathological findings is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continuous inflammatory reaction of the colon","Superficial ulcerations","Inflammatory process confined to the mucosa and submucosa","Micro-abscesses within crypts","Non-caseating granulomas"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom the history, there is a strong likelihood that this patient has inflammatory bowel disease. The colonic findings of two skip lesions is suggestive of Crohn\u0027s disease. Crohn\u0027s disease findings on pathology are characterised by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELinear mucosal ulcerations\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiscontinuous (skip) lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransmural inflammatory process\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-caseating granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to distinguish Crohn\u0027s disease from ulcerative colitis (UC) to ensure appropriate management. Ulcerative colitis differs in its pathophysiology to Crohn\u0027s in that UC is usually found in the rectum (although in rare cases the rectum may be spared) and can lead to involvement of the entire colon in a gross inflammatory process without skip lesions (pancolitis). Histologically in UC, this \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory process is\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Econfined to the mucosa and submucosa\u003C/strong\u003E, with \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial ulcerations\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecrypt micro-abscesses\u003C/strong\u003E commonly associated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe finding of \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-caseating granulomas\u003C/strong\u003E is virtually diagnostic of Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pathological findings associated with Crohn\u0027s disease include linear mucosal ulcerations, \u0027skip\u0027 lesions, transmural inflammation and non-caseating granulomas"],"references":["Hendrickson BA, Gokhale R, Cho JH. Clinical aspects and pathophysiology of inflammatory bowel disease. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2002;15(1):79-94. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11781268/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12018"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-06T21:08:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-06T21:08:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44100"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"crea